high_control: When I was about 12 years old I was fishing with a group of neighbors.  When we were leaving, Corky through a rock into a large puddle of water just as our friend Mike was jumping across the puddle. The rock hit Mike in the head and knocked him unconscious. I reacted by quickly moving Mike from the water so he would not drown and running to a near by house and calling an ambulance.  When the ambulance arrived I took them to where Mike was.  In the end, Mike was not severely hurt but was hospitalized with a concussion.I felt good about myself.  I reached when my other friends did not, and was commended for doing so by the firemen and police.

I have a long drive to and from my office. I find this drive, along 280, through the mountains of Northern California, to be not only relaxing, but a time of complete control. I have control over my commute, how fast I drive, which lane I choose to drive in, and what I listen to while driving. It's a time when I can take control over my day and makes me feel like, regardless of how my day went, I have some little bit of control over my life.

A few years ago, I was alone in a dorm room late in the evening, and I started feeling a toothache caused by a wisdom tooth. I ignored it at first then took some pain killers. Nothing helped with the pain.It was during the weekend and most friends and neighbors were gone. I had to take full control of the situation.As the pain was becoming unbearable, I called an emergency line and had them send a dentist to my place. He came and gave me an injection to relieve the pain. He said it would take a while before it works. I asked for more injections I could take by myself in the future, filled the paperwork and sat quietly in my room waiting for the pain to go away. It wasn't long before I was able to lie down and fall asleep.
